<i>mede</i> ‘mead, alcoholic drink of fermented honey and water’, possibly denoting one who was fond of the drink or who made or sold mead. Compare   Meader  ."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":62,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":71,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":82,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":84,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Simon Thomas Meade was born in 1487, in Gilston, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 2 daughters with Anne Moody. He died in 1592, in Earls Colne, Essex, England, at the age of 105."},"et":{"1487–1592  ":"1487–1592","1500–Female":"1500–Surnud","1525–1554":"1525–1554","1525–1584":"1525–1584","1487–1592":"1487–1592","Feb 1584":"veebruar 1584","1571":"1571","1592":"1592","1525":"1525","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1554":"1554","1487":"1487","1554 ":"1554","1584":"1584","1525  ":"1525","1592  ":"1592","1549":"1549","St Dunstan and All Saints, London, England":"All Saints Church, West Ham, London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Earls Colne, Essex, England":"Earls Colne, Essex, England","Braintree, Essex, England":"Braintree, Essex, England","Gilston, Hertfordshire, England":"Gilston, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1487–1592  ":"1487–1592","1500–Female":"1500–Kuollut","1525–1554":"1525–1554","1525–1584":"1525–1584","